BinaryLesson.createStepper({containerId:'ps-m-why',steps:[{title:'The problem: one loop does everything',html:'<p class="text-gray-300 mb-3">When movement and animation share one <code class="bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-yellow-300">while True:</code> loop, a single <code class="bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-yellow-300">wait()</code> slows the <em>entire</em> loop — including how fast the game responds to key presses.</p><div class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-4 mb-1 border-l-4 border-red-500"><div class="text-red-400 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">❌ One thread — sluggish controls</div><pre class="text-green-400 font-mono text-sm">def game_start():
    while True:
        if key_pressed("right"):
            change_x(5)
        if key_pressed("left"):
            change_x(-5)
        next_costume()
        wait(0.1)  # limits whole loop to 10/sec</pre></div>',note:'The wait(0.1) forces the entire loop to run only 10 times per second. That includes the key checks — so the sprite can take up to 0.1 seconds to react to a key press. Noticeably laggy.'},{title:'The fix: separate threads',html:'<p class="text-gray-300 mb-3">Each PyScratch thread runs independently. Splitting movement and animation into two threads means each one runs on its own schedule.</p><div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-3 mb-1"><div class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-3 border-l-4 border-blue-500"><div class="text-blue-400 text-xs font-bold uppercase mb-2">✅ Thread 1 — movement</div><pre class="text-green-400 font-mono text-xs">def game_start():
    while True:
        if key_pressed("right"):
            change_x(5)
        if key_pressed("left"):
            change_x(-5)
        if_on_edge_bounce()</pre></div><div class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-3 border-l-4 border-purple-500"><div class="text-purple-400 text-xs font-bold uppercase mb-2">✅ Thread 2 — animation</div><pre class="text-green-400 font-mono text-xs">def game_start():
    while True:
        if key_pressed("right") \
           or key_pressed("left"):
            next_costume()
        else:
            set_costume(1)
        wait(0.1)</pre></div></div>',note:'Thread 1 checks keys up to 60 times per second. Thread 2 updates the costume 10 times per second — and only when actually moving. Neither blocks the other.'},{title:'The rule: wait() only pauses its own thread',html:'<div class="bg-gray-900 rounded-lg p-4 mb-1"><ul class="text-gray-300 space-y-3"><li>✅ <strong class="text-white">Movement thread</strong> — runs every frame. Keys respond in under 17 ms.</li><li>✅ <strong class="text-white">Animation thread</strong> — checks movement keys 10 times per second; only advances the costume when a key is held.</li><li>✅ <code class="bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-yellow-300">wait()</code> only pauses the thread it is called from. The other thread keeps running.</li><li>🔑 <strong class="text-white">Rule:</strong> put <code class="bg-gray-700 px-1 rounded text-yellow-300">wait()</code> in a thread only when you want <em>that thread</em> to slow down.</li></ul></div>',note:'This is the core advantage of threads: independent timing. A slow animation thread can never make the controls feel unresponsive.'}]});

